\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Scala is the undisputed heavyweight champion of big data.
 It makes sense,
 then,
 that its collections are where the language outshines almost everything else.
 While other languages treat lists as simple storage,
 Scala treats them as high-speed engines for transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our company example,
 it would be nice if we had a way to track collections of companies so we didn't need to keep a rolodex around.
 In addition to a list of all companies,
 it would also be nice if we had a way to keep track of the companies we planned to meet with in the upcoming week.
 Both of these are containers that hold one or more objects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of these will need similar sets of methods:
 add a company,
 remove a company,
 and give us a list of companies,
 etc.
 Let's work on building a ComanyList class to handle these things.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Big Three:
 Lists,
 Vectors,
 and Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Scala,
 we typically reach for three primary containers.
 By default,
 these are immutable.
 You don't "change" a list;
 you create a new,
 refined version of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our CompanyList,
 we will explore the first 2 as options.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Lists:
 The Bread and Butter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A List is an ordered sequence of items,
 ideal for small to medium-sized data.
 Each item occupies a spot in the list,
 referenced by non-negative integers.
 You can create lists with literals,
 but you can also create from existing ones - specifying what should change in the new one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val fruit = List("Apple",
 "Banana",
 "Cherry")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val first = fruit(0) // "Apple"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Prepending (Adding to the front)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val moreFruit = "Dragonfruit" ::
 fruit 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Updating (Creating a new list with one change)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val kiwiList = fruit.updated(2,
 "Kiwi") 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scala uses () for indexing rather than [],
 a small departure from C-style languages that hints at Scala's mathematical roots.
 In general,
 though,
 we want to use the lift/get operator which returns a nice option (giving us 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Some
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 / 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

None
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 instead).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scala also provides powerful tools like .patch to perform surgery on your data as you create new lists:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Remove 1 element at index 1,
 and insert "Lemon" and "Lime"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val citruses = fruit.patch(1,
 List("Lemon",
 "Lime"),
 1) // Apple,
 Cherry,
 Lemon,
 Lime
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 like Ruby,
 we can actually do some overriding of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

()
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operator by overriding the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

apply
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 method in subclasses of lists:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
class SafeList(items:
 List[String]) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  // This "overrides" the () syntax
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  def apply(index:
 Int):
 String = {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    if (index >= 0 && index < items.length) {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
      items(index) // Calls the underlying list's apply
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    } else {
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
      "Whoops!
 Out of bounds."
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
    }
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  }
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Usage
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val mySafeList = new SafeList(List("Scala",
 "sttp",
 "Doobie"))
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
println(mySafeList(1))  // Output:
 "sttp"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slice operator is a convenient operator that returns a range of items within a list:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Get elements from index 1 to 2 (exclusive of 3)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val middle = citruses.slice(1,
 3) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Result:
 List(Cherry,
 Lemon)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we mentioned,
 lists are immutable,
 but we create new lists with different values at specified indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many other operators for lists that are worth looking into,
 like take and drop and many others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Maps:
 The Dictionary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Map (often called a Hash or Dictionary) is quite similar to lists as collections of indexed options.
 Maps,
 however,
 store pairs of keys and values.
 There is no sequencing requirement here;
 you just need to know the key.
 The example below creates the map as a literal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val meal = Map(
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  "main" -> "Lobster",
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
  "starter" -> "Escargots"
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val appy = meal("starter") // "Escargots"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Map elements are not ordered in any particular way.
 However,
 despite this,
 they are a very popular data structure in scala.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To create new maps we again make copies from existing ones:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val userRoles = Map("Alice" -> "Admin",
 "Bob" -> "User")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
// Replace Bob's role
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val updatedRoles = userRoles + ("Bob" -> "SuperUser")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also add / replace multiple keys at once:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val batchUpdate = userRoles ++ Map("Alice" -> "Owner",
 "Bob" -> "Admin")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again,
 there are many interesting operations to take list creation further,
 like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

updateWith
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 and it's worth taking a deeper look when you have time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Vectors:
 The Random-Access Specialist
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just a quick note about the last of the big 3 containers:
 the vectors.
 If your dataset is enormous and you need to jump to the middle of it instantly,
 use a Vector.
 While a List has to walk from the beginning to find the 10,000th element,
 a Vector can "teleport" there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val trees = Vector("Pine",
 "Birch",
 "Maple")
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
val middle = trees(trees.length / 2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Addtionally,
 updating an element in a vector is much faster as well (close to constant),
 so large lists needing replacements are also well accommodated here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Back to our CompanyList Container
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With our newfound knowledge,
 let's return to our CompanyList container.
 To make things interesting,
 let's come up with some operations we would like to implement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
append(company) -> list
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
delete_first() -> company
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
delete_last() -> company
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
(index) -> company
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
with_name(name) -> company
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider how to implement this.
 We need to be able to add to the start of the list,
 remove from the start and the end,
 as well as grabbing an element at a given index.
 These all seem to point to a list.
 However,
 on closer thought,
 deleting from the end of a *list* is actually O(n),
 since lists are implemented in such a way as to require looking at each element until we come to the end in order to know which is the last.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors,
 however,
 have no such restriction,
 and actually remain close to constant operation time on append,
 delete from start *and* end,
 and indexing.
 so we will go with that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The one question mark is the capability to return an element by it's name.
 But as we have pointed out in the intro,
 scala is very adept at filtering a list by name,
 so likely a map is not warranted here – we can simply search.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know we can start by creating a class for the CompanyList.
 We will give it a list to hold the songs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
